{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ba6071e-2f01-47e2-bd81-623d0675e92e","content":"There's no `SettingsPage.xaml` in the working directory, so I'll show you the pattern directly.\n\n## Converting to Compiled Bindings\n\nAdd `x:DataType` to your `ContentPage` root element pointing at your ViewModel:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout>\n        <Entry Text=\"{Binding Theme}\" />\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n        <Slider Value=\"{Binding FontSize}\" />\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe `{Binding ...}` markup stays the same — the compiler now resolves them at build time against `SettingsViewModel`.\n\n## Catching Binding Errors at Build Time\n\nWith `x:DataType` declared, the XAML compiler validates every `{Binding}` path. A typo like `{Binding Themee}` becomes a **build error** (e.g., `XC0045: property 'Themee' not found on 'SettingsViewModel'`).\n\nTo ensure this is active:\n\n1. **Keep XamlC enabled** (it's on by default in .NET MAUI):\n   ```csharp\n   [assembly: XamlCompilation(XamlCompilationOptions.Compile)]\n   ```\n\n2. **Treat warnings as errors** (optional, for strictness) in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <TreatWarningsAsErrors>true</TreatWarningsAsErrors>\n   ```\n\n3. **Avoid `x:DataType` suppression** — if you need an untyped binding in a subtree (e.g., a `DataTemplate` with a different type), set a new `x:DataType` on that element rather than using `x:DataType=\"\"` to disable it.\n\nThat's it — no runtime reflection, faster bindings, and misspelled property names fail the build.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0489c0e-e956-4f20-a6de-bff80825357e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty and there's no SettingsPage.xaml file. The user is asking a conceptual question about how to convert their page to use compiled bindings. I'll provide the answer directly since there's no file to modify.","outputTokens":615,"requestId":"4842:2ADC27:748BD63:80D975C:69F3FA49"},"id":"ea2c6148-be6c-43e8-b0d3-7a278047bee6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:56:56.854Z","parentId":"53543499-a52a-4908-b21b-037813b54cd6"}
